<h1>What is TOMOYO Linux?</h1>

<p>TOMOYO Linux is an access analysis/restriction tool for Linux systems. The project was launched in March 2003 and is sponsored by NTT DATA Corporation, Japan.</p>

<p>In an operating system (OS), each program or process is not monitored. It is difficult for you to figure out what is happening in your system:</p>

<img src="disabled.png" alt="disabled.png" width="500" height="350">

<p>By introducing TOMOYO Linux into your Linux systems, 
TOMOYO Linux automatically records access requests from each program or process are as access control lists (so-called <b>security policy configuration</b> or <b>policy configuration</b>):</p>

<img src="learning.png" alt="learning.png" width="500" height="350">

<p>By browsing policy configuration generated by TOMOYO Linux, you can figure out what is happening in your system:</p>

<img src="permissive.png" alt="permissive.png" width="500" height="350">

<p>Thus, you can use TOMOYO Linux for analysis purposes:</p>

<ul>
<li>Debugging applications</li>
<li>Understanding the system's behavior</li>
<li>Writing textbooks and documentation</li>
</ul>

<p>If you enable enforcing mode (this functionality is so-called <b>Mandatory Access Control</b> or <b>MAC</b>), each program or process becomes monitored and restricted by policy configuration:</p>

<img src="enforcing.png" alt="enforcing.png" width="500" height="350">

<p>Thus, you can use TOMOYO Linux for restriction purposes:</p>

<ul>
<li>Restricting SSH based services</li>
<li>Restricting system administrator's operations</li>
<li>Per application/user networking firewalls</li>
<li>Baseline parameter checking for every application (e.g. Web server's CGI)</li>
<li>Reducing damage caused by buffer overflows and OS command injection vulnerability</li>
<li>Deploying honey pot system</li>
<li>Suited well to Linux based PCs, servers, embedded systems</li>
</ul>

<p>A system protected by MAC helps to reduce the damage done when an application is compromised. An important part of MAC is the creation and management of policy configuration for every process in a system, which requires knowledge of precisely what each process should be allowed to do. This may sound like a fiendishly difficult task and it requires a high degree of understanding and skill. However, <b>TOMOYO Linux provides the ability to generate policy configuration automatically</b> and can make securing a system very easy. Any experienced Linux administrator can set up and use TOMOYO Linux within a day!</p>

<h1>How can I try TOMOYO Linux?</h1>

<p><a href="http://tomoyo.sourceforge.jp/1.8/index.html.en">TOMOYO Linux 1.x</a> is the original branch of development, which was first released on 11th November 2005 under the GPL. It was implemented as a patch that can be applied to the Linux kernel and is still in active development.</p>

<p><a href="http://tomoyo.sourceforge.jp/2.3/index.html.en">TOMOYO Linux 2.x</a> is the Linux mainline kernel branch of development. In June 2009, a subset of TOMOYO functionality was merged into the Linux kernel 2.6.30 and makes use of standard Linux Security Module (LSM) hooks. However, the LSM hooks must be extended further in order to port the full MAC functionality of TOMOYO Linux 1.x into the Linux kernel. Thus, it does not yet provide equal functionality with the 1.x branch of development but will do in the future. This <a href="http://tomoyo.sourceforge.jp/comparison.html.en">feature comparison chart</a> compares the current differences between each branch.</p>

<p>Once you have decided which version of TOMOYO Linux you require, see the sections below for further information.</p>

<br>

<hr>

<h2><a href="http://tomoyo.sourceforge.jp/2.3/index.html.en">Mainlined version (2.x series)</a></h2>

<p>Use this version if your priority is to use TOMOYO Linux without modifying the kernel, and you do not require all of the features of the 1.x branch.</p>

